{
  "integrative": {
    "title": "Integrative Close: Circuit Design Calculation",
    "objective": "Synthesize Pythagoras' Theorem, formula transposition, and percentage limits to verify a circuit's design suitability.",
    "retrievalTextLines": [
      "To finalize a circuit design, you must often combine several mathematical tools in sequence. You start by finding the total opposition to current (Impedance) using Pythagoras' Theorem for the resistance and reactance components.",
      "Once you have the total Impedance (Z), you must transpose Ohm's Law (V = I × Z) to find the actual current (I) that will flow. Finally, you apply a percentage-based safety check to ensure the calculated current does not exceed the recommended loading limit of the protective device."
    ],
    "questionText": "An AC circuit has a Resistance (R) of 12 Ω and a Reactance (X) of 16 Ω. \n\n1. Calculate the total Impedance (Z) using Pythagoras' Theorem.\n2. Calculate the current (I) flowing in the circuit if the supply voltage is 230V.\n3. If the circuit is protected by a 16A breaker, is the current within the 80% maximum loading limit (which is 12.8A)?",
    "answerGuidance": [
      "1. Impedance (Z) = 20 Ω",
      "2. Current (I) = 11.5 A",
      "3. Yes, 11.5A is within the 12.8A limit."
    ],
    "hint": "First, square 12 and 16, add them, and find the square root for Z. Then, divide 230 by your Z value to find the current. Finally, compare that current to 12.8A."
  }
